		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/10/unpredictable-work-hours-chaotic-life/" data-title="Unpredictable Work Hours, Chaotic Life" data-description="Irregular and on-call scheduling increases workersâ stress and family conflicts, recent research shows.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/10/opinion/10tritchWEB2/10tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/10/opinion/10tritchWEB2/10tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/10/opinion/10tritchWEB2/10tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003845976" width="480" height="356" alt="Demonstrators protest low wages and working conditions at various retail outlets."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="356"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Demonstrators protest low wages and working conditions at various retail outlets.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Ruth Fremson/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The tyranny of erratic work schedules is obvious to employees who donât know what their schedules will be tomorrow or have to call in to see if there is work. And the effects have been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/02/22/business/late-to-bed-early-to-rise-and-working-tired.html?_r=0">well documented</a> in <a href="//www.cnbc.com/2013/12/04/how-on-call-hours-are-hurting-part-time-workers.html">articles</a> and <a href="//www.nwlc.org/sites/default/files/pdfs/workers_accounts_of_the_fallout_from_difficult_scheduling_practices_2015_final.pdf">oral histories</a>. Increasingly, the anecdotal evidence is being confirmed by research.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A <a href="//www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00140139.2015.1046498">recent paper</a> in the peer-reviewed journal <a href="//www.tandfonline.com/loi/terg20#.VcPDHPkYG48">Ergonomics</a> looked at Dutch workers who were on call when they were not scheduled to work. It found that being on-call, even when one is not called, decreases an employeeâs well-being and increases the need for ârecovery,â (read: sleep and time off).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other research reviewed in the paper also found increased stress, anxiety, irritation, fatigue and family conflicts among on-call workers. One possible reason is that not knowing whether one will be called is a stressor in itself. Another is that being on call makes it hard to detach from work and recoup. One paper found that without a chance to recover, extra effort has to be exerted at the start of each work period âto rebalance the suboptimal psychological stateâ (read: to face the day). Chronic need for recovery, the research notes, âmight lead to long-term ill health.â (How could it not?)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The American experience appears to be worse than the situations studied above. The Dutch workers in the Ergonomics study, for example, knew in advance when they would be on call. They were also men employed in technical fields.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the United States, it is not uncommon for employers to give little advance notice of work hours and instead require workers to call in or wait to be called to find out if they need to report to work. Such scheduling is most prevalent among the nationâs 20 million low-wage workers, most of whom are women and many of whom work in retail or food service.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Estimates of the share of American workers with irregular and on-call work schedules range from 10 percent to nearly 20 percent, according to government and private surveys cited in a <a href="//www.epi.org/publication/irregular-work-scheduling-and-its-consequences/">recent paper</a> by Lonnie Golden, a professor of economics at Pennsylvania State University. In one survey, almost 20 percent of workers said they had âa day or lessâ advance notice of their work hours and days. An additional 12 percent reported advance notice of two to three days and 12 percent had notice of four days to a week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not surprisingly, 26 percent of employees with irregular and on-call schedules report frequent work-family conflict versus 11 percent of those with regular schedules. Irregular and on-call work was also associated with higher stress on the job.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But if irregular and on-call work is so bad, why is it increasingly prevalent? Jodi Kantor of The Times explored the question <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/08/13/us/starbucks-workers-scheduling-hours.html?_r=0">here</a>. The answer is that scheduling has become a tool to increase profits. Software lets employers pinpoint when and where they need workers, depending on weekly, daily and even hourly sales patterns and on other variables, including the weather or merchandise delivery times. Managers are often compensated on the leanness of their staffing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">None of this makes irregular and on-call scheduling right or good. Labor costs could also be reduced if child labor were legal or if there were no minimum wage. In addition, employers could save big money if there were no on-the-job health and safety rules. But it is illegal to make workers sick with harmful substances and unsafe conditions. It also should be illegal to make them sick with irregular and on-call schedules.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The issue affects everyone. Irregular and on-call scheduling puts the short-term profit of companies above the long-term health of the economy. It is linked to low and variable earnings that hurt consumer spending and, by extension, economic growth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Employers use irregular and on-call schedules because they can. Legislation introduced <a href="//www.nwlc.org/resource/schedules-work-act-giving-workers-tools-they-need-succeed">in Congress</a> and <a href="//www.nwlc.org/resource/recently-introduced-and-enacted-state-and-local-fair-scheduling-legislation">in the states</a> would curb the practice. Hereâs to fighting and winning the battles.</p>
	</div>
